n employed as a metaphor with no special visual content. What distinguishes pictorial devices as resources for doing science, and the special problems that are raised by the mere presence of visual elements in scientific treatises, tends to be overlooked.The contributors to this volume examine the historical and philosophical issues concerning the role that scientific illustration plays in the creation of scientific knowledge. They regard both text and picture as resources that scientists employ in their practical activities, their value as scientific resources deriving from their ability to convey information.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArt and sciencexHistory. 0aArt and sciencexPhilosophy. 0aScientific illustrationxHistory. 0aScientific illustrationxPhilosophy. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aBaigrie, Brian S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaigrie, Brian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrown, James Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiere, Ronald N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Bert S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemp, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoser, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Hara, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuse, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTopper, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-